        %h2 State of the Union
        %h3 Current challenges and opportunities


        %p From the junior developer with just a handful of years’ experience to the software professional who’s been in the game for decades, we set out to see how the people behind the software are dealing with a rapidly changing technology landscape.

        %p We examined overall attitudes and perceptions on the state of culture, workflow, and tooling within IT organizations with the goal to uncover any disparities between developers and IT management. We also looked at how remote versus in-office cultures are faring, compared the attitudes of agile and DevOps teams, and exposed the trends propelling high-performing teams.

        %p
          This year, we confirmed that
          = link_to "high-performing", "#methodology", class: "js-smoothscroll"
          teams are more likely to report having a strong DevOps culture, resulting in better visibility and collaboration than their lower-functioning counterparts. High-performing teams also report having better access to the best development tools, spend less time context switching, and are more likely to be using cloud-based tools. For leaders of high-performing teams, automating the software development lifecycle is a top priority.

